{"id":"polygons","locale":"en","nextCourse":"polyhedra","prevCourse":"pd","title":"Angles and Polygons","description":"Angles, Angles in Polygons, Drawing Triangles, Pythagoras’ Theorem, The Coordinate Plane, Transformations and Congruence","color":"#2E6AE1","level":"Foundations","icon":"/content/polygons/icon.png","hero":"\\content\\polygons\\hero.jpg","goals":13,"sections":[{"id":"angles","title":"Angles","locked":true,"url":"/course/polygons/angles","steps":["step-0"],"goals":0,"duration":5},{"id":"angles-in-polygons","title":"Angles in Polygons","locked":true,"url":"/course/polygons/angles-in-polygons","steps":["step-1"],"goals":0,"duration":5},{"id":"triangles","title":"Drawing Triangles","url":"/course/polygons/triangles","steps":["triangle-inequality","triangle-inequality-1","inequality-picker","triangle-inequality-2","triangle-inequality-3","step-7"],"goals":13,"duration":15},{"id":"pythagoras","title":"Pythagoras’ Theorem","locked":true,"url":"/course/polygons/pythagoras","steps":["step-8"],"goals":0,"duration":5},{"id":"coordinate-plane","title":"The Coordinate Plane","locked":true,"url":"/course/polygons/coordinate-plane","steps":["step-9"],"goals":0,"duration":5},{"id":"transformations","title":"Transformations and Congruence","locked":true,"url":"/course/polygons/transformations","steps":["step-10"],"goals":0,"duration":5}],"steps":{"step-0":{"id":"step-0","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-0\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]},"step-1":{"id":"step-1","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-1\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]},"triangle-inequality":{"id":"triangle-inequality","title":"Triangle Inequality","html":"<x-step id=\"triangle-inequality\" goals=\"s0 s1 s3 s5 blank-0\"><p>In this section, we will explore how we can draw triangles. For example, if I give you any three numbers, can you make a triangle that has those side lengths?</p><p>Here are a some examples – move the vertices of the triangle until the three sides match one of the triples on the left.</p><div class=\"inequality row\"><div style=\"width:150px\"><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"t-num\">5</div><div class=\"t-num\">6</div><div class=\"t-num\">7</div> <span class=\"check\" data-when=\"s0\"></span></div><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"t-num\">3</div><div class=\"t-num\">9</div><div class=\"t-num\">9</div> <span class=\"check\" data-when=\"s1\"></span></div><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"t-num\">2</div><div class=\"t-num\">4</div><div class=\"t-num\">8</div></div><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"t-num\">4</div><div class=\"t-num\">6</div><div class=\"t-num\">7</div> <span class=\"check\" data-when=\"s3\"></span></div><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"t-num\">1</div><div class=\"t-num\">2</div><div class=\"t-num\">6</div></div><div class=\"item\"><div class=\"t-num\">3</div><div class=\"t-num\">5</div><div class=\"t-num\">7</div> <span class=\"check\" data-when=\"s5\"></span></div></div><div class=\"grow\"><x-geopad class=\"label-halo\" height=\"360\"><svg><circle class=\"move pulsate\" name=\"a\" cx=\"175\" cy=\"75\"></circle><circle class=\"move\" name=\"b\" cx=\"150\" cy=\"250\"></circle><circle class=\"move\" name=\"c\" cx=\"350\" cy=\"200\"></circle><path class=\"red\" x=\"segment(a,b)\" label=\"${roundD(a,b)}\"></path><path class=\"blue\" x=\"segment(b,c)\" label=\"${roundD(b,c)}\"></path><path class=\"yellow\" x=\"segment(a,c)\" label=\"${roundD(a,c)}\"></path></svg></x-geopad></div></div><p class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"s0 s1 s3 s5\"> It seems like there are a few cases where three numbers simply <em>cannot</em> make a triangle. This particularly happens when one side <x-blank-mc goal=\"blank-0\"><button class=\"choice\">is much longer than</button><button class=\"choice\">is much shorter than</button><button class=\"choice\">is the same length as</button></x-blank-mc> the other two.</p></x-step>","goals":["s0","s1","s3","s5","blank-0"],"keywords":[]},"triangle-inequality-1":{"id":"triangle-inequality-1","title":"Triangle Inequality  ","html":"<x-step id=\"triangle-inequality-1\" goals=\"next-0\"><div class=\"row padded\"><div class=\"grow\"> <p>Think about the three sides of a triangle as metal rods, connected with hinges. Let’s place the <span class=\"step-target pill\" tabindex=\"0\" data-to=\"long\">longest rod</span> in the middle and the <span class=\"step-target pill\" tabindex=\"0\" data-to=\"short\">shorter ones</span> on either side.</p><p class=\"r\"> Now it is easy to see that it is impossible to link up the ends of the shorter rods, if their combined length is less than the length of the larger rod. <button class=\"next-step\">Continue</button></p></div><div style=\"width: 300px\"> <x-geopad width=\"300\" height=\"180\"><svg><circle name=\"a\" x=\"point(90,90)\"></circle><circle name=\"b\" x=\"point(210,90)\"></circle><circle class=\"move pulsate\" name=\"c\" cx=\"150\" cy=\"50\" project=\"circle(a,60)\"></circle><circle class=\"move pulsate\" name=\"d\" cx=\"150\" cy=\"50\" project=\"circle(b,40)\"></circle><path class=\"blue\" x=\"circle(a,60)\" style=\"stroke-dasharray: 8px 10px\"></path><path class=\"blue\" x=\"circle(b,40)\" style=\"stroke-dasharray: 8px 10px\"></path><path class=\"thick\" x=\"segment(a,b)\" target=\"long\"></path><path class=\"thick\" x=\"segment(a,c)\" target=\"short\"></path><path class=\"thick\" x=\"segment(b,d)\" target=\"short\"></path></svg></x-geopad></div></div> </x-step>","goals":["next-0"],"keywords":[]},"inequality-picker":{"id":"inequality-picker","title":"Inequality Picker","html":"<x-step id=\"inequality-picker\" goals=\"picker-0 picker-2 picker-5\"><p>Let’s rewrite this observation in mathematical terms:</p><div class=\"theorem\"> <p><strong>The Triangle Inequality</strong><br> The sum of the lengths of any two sides of a triangle must be greater than the length of the third.</p></div> <p>In other words, if a triangle has sides <em>a</em>, <em>b</em> and <em>c</em>, then we know that <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_a_ plus _b_ is greater than _c_\"><mi>a</mi><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo value=\">\">&gt;</mo><mi>c</mi></span> and <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_a_ plus _c_ is greater than _b_\"><mi>a</mi><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo value=\">\">&gt;</mo><mi>b</mi></span> and <span class=\"nowrap\"><span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"_b_ plus _c_ is greater than _a_\"><mi>b</mi><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo value=\">\">&gt;</mo><mi>a</mi></span>.</span></p><p>The triangle inequality allows us to quickly check if three numbers can make a triangle. Which of these triples of numbers are possible?</p><x-picker goal=\"picker\"><div class=\"item text-center\"><div class=\"t-num\">4</div><div class=\"t-num\">6</div><div class=\"t-num\">9</div></div><div class=\"item text-center\" data-error=\"inequality-error-1\"><div class=\"t-num\">1</div><div class=\"t-num\">2</div><div class=\"t-num\">3</div></div><div class=\"item text-center\"><div class=\"t-num\">3</div><div class=\"t-num\">7</div><div class=\"t-num\">8</div></div><div class=\"item text-center\" data-error=\"inequality-error-2\"><div class=\"t-num\">2</div><div class=\"t-num\">4</div><div class=\"t-num\">7</div></div><div class=\"item text-center\" data-error=\"inequality-error-3\"><div class=\"t-num\">1</div><div class=\"t-num\">5</div><div class=\"t-num\">8</div></div><div class=\"item text-center\"><div class=\"t-num\">2</div><div class=\"t-num\">3</div><div class=\"t-num\">4</div></div></x-picker></x-step>","goals":["picker-0","picker-2","picker-5"],"keywords":[]},"triangle-inequality-2":{"id":"triangle-inequality-2","title":"Triangle Inequality  ","html":"<x-step id=\"triangle-inequality-2\" goals=\"blank-0 blank-1\"><p>The triangle inequality also allows us to estimate the length of the third side of a triangle, if we know the length of the other two.</p><p>Imagine that a triangle has two sides of length 4 and 6. Let’s call <em>c</em> the length of the third side. Then we know that</p><p class=\"text-center\"> <span class=\"nowrap\"><span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"4 plus 6 is greater than _c_\"><mn>4</mn><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mn>6</mn><mo value=\">\">&gt;</mo><mi>c</mi></span>,</span> <span class=\"space\"></span> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"4 plus _c_ is greater than 6\"><mn>4</mn><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo value=\">\">&gt;</mo><mn>6</mn></span> <span class=\"space\"></span> and <span class=\"space\"></span> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"6 plus _c_ is greater than 4\"><mn>6</mn><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mi>c</mi><mo value=\">\">&gt;</mo><mn>4</mn></span></p><p>We can rearrange these inequalities to give <x-blank solution=\"2\" goal=\"blank-0\"></x-blank> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"is less than _c_ is less than\"><mo value=\"<\">&lt;</mo><mi>c</mi><mo value=\"<\">&lt;</mo></span> <span class=\"nowrap\"><x-blank solution=\"10\" goal=\"blank-1\"></x-blank>.</span> <span class=\"reveal\" data-when=\"blank-0 blank-1\">The length of side <em>c</em> has to be between 2 and 10.</span></p></x-step>","goals":["blank-0","blank-1"],"keywords":[]},"triangle-inequality-3":{"id":"triangle-inequality-3","title":"Triangle Inequality  ","html":"<x-step id=\"triangle-inequality-3\" goals=\"target-0 target-1\"><div class=\"row padded\"><div class=\"grow\"> <p>Once again, we can think about this using physical objects: two sides of the triangle are metal rods of length 4 and 6, and the third side is a rubber band that can expand or contract.</p><p>Now you can see that the length of the rubber band will always be <button class=\"var-action\" @click=\"hover(90,45,118,69,1)\">at least</button> <span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"6 minus 4 equals 2\"><mn>6</mn><mo value=\"−\">−</mo><mn>4</mn><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mn>2</mn></span> and <button class=\"var-action\" @click=\"hover(50,127,250,127,0)\">at most</button> <span class=\"nowrap\"><span class=\"math\" data-voice=\"6 plus 4 equals 10\"><mn>6</mn><mo value=\"+\">+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo value=\"=\">=</mo><mn>10</mn></span>.</span></p></div><div style=\"width: 300px\"> <x-geopad width=\"300\" height=\"200\"><svg><circle name=\"a\" cx=\"170\" cy=\"130\" hidden=\"hidden\"></circle><circle class=\"move\" name=\"b\" cx=\"75\" cy=\"60\" project=\"circle(a,120)\"></circle><circle class=\"move\" name=\"c\" cx=\"300\" cy=\"110\" project=\"circle(a,80)\"></circle><path class=\"thick\" x=\"segment(a,b)\" label=\"6\"></path><path class=\"thick\" x=\"segment(a,c)\" label=\"4\"></path><path class=\"orange\" x=\"segment(b,c)\" label=\"${round(distance(b,c)/20,1)}\"></path></svg></x-geopad></div></div> <p>Note that these are <em>strict</em> inequalities. If the third side is <em>exactly</em> 2 or 10, we get a straight line and not a triangle. However, 2.1 or 9.9 would be enough to form a triangle.</p></x-step>","goals":["target-0","target-1"],"keywords":[]},"step-7":{"id":"step-7","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-7\" goals=\"\"><p class=\"todo\"> COMING SOON – More on drawing triangles, angles in triangles, similarity and congruence.</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]},"step-8":{"id":"step-8","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-8\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]},"step-9":{"id":"step-9","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-9\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]},"step-10":{"id":"step-10","title":"Step  ","html":"<x-step id=\"step-10\" goals=\"\"><p>TODO</p></x-step>","goals":[],"keywords":[]}},"availableLocales":["en"],"biosJSON":"{}","glossJSON":"{}","hintsJSON":"{\"welcome\":\"<p>Welcome to Mathigon! I’m Archie, your personal tutor. <img class=\\\"emoji\\\" width=\\\"20\\\" height=\\\"20\\\" src=\\\"https://static.mathigon.org/emoji/graduation-cap.png\\\" alt=\\\"graduation-cap\\\"></p>\",\"account\":\"<p>You can <x-target class=\\\"step-target pill\\\" to=\\\"#login-btn\\\">create a free account</x-target> to save your progress.</p>\",\"tutorial1\":\"<p>Our content is divided into